Macedonians in a referendum on changing the name of the country
In a referendum on Sunday, the Macedonians voted to change the name of the country to the "North Macedonia Republic", which would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece, which has prevented the country's aspirations to become a member of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, believes that the name of the northern neighbour is in practice a regional requirement for its territory and has therefore opposed its membership of the EU and NATO.
In June, the governments of the countries agreed on a new name proposal, but nationalist opponents felt that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has announced that he will not vote in a referendum, and the campaign against the vote casts doubt as to whether the turnout will reach the required 50% threshold in order to make the result legal.
The question on the ballot was: "Are you on the side of NATO and EU membership, accepting the agreement with Greece".
Proponents of name change such as Prime Minister Zoran Zaev argue that the price should be paid in order to allow Macedonia, which emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia, to become a member of both the EU and NATO.
"I came today to vote for the future of our country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live in freedom as members of the European Union because it means a safer life for all of us," said 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although the vote is not legally binding, enough Members have said that they respect the outcome of the vote in order to have a decisive impact.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
According to the Central Electoral Commission, no irregularities had been reported by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16, compared to 34 per cent of the previous 2016 parliamentary elections, when 66 per cent of those entitled to vote finally cast their votes.
"I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe," said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in a referendum on Macedonia's name change in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018. The name change would open the way to NATO and EU membership .
A 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of tents erected by boycotters in front of the Skopje Parliament.
"We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join the heads upright, not through the kitchen door," said Kavadarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want to take us as Macedonia, we can turn elsewhere, such as China and Russia, as part of the integration of the euro area".
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership brings needed investment to Macedonia, with an unemployment rate of more than 20%.
"I believe a large majority will vote in favour of a name change because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," said Zaev after giving his vote.
He said the "yes" voice was our "requesting future."
The opinion poll published by the Macedonian Institute of Political Research on Monday referred to a turnout of between 30% and 43% in the referendum - below the required level of activity.
In another poll conducted by Telma TV, Macedonia, 57 per cent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
70% of them said they would vote in favour of the yes option.
In order for the referendum to succeed, the turnout must exceed 50% by one vote.
