Harvard students complete an adequate course of rest instruction
All undergraduate students at Harvard University will take a course this year to increase the student's rest. The course is a counterattack to the university's thriving macho culture, where students weigh a long night with caffeine power.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite ignorant of basic matters related to their own well-being.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler of Harvard University Medical Faculty, who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, believes that the course is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler received an idea for the course after lecturing about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing about it now, in my last year of study?'
No one had ever told him about the need for a dream, which I thought was surprising," he told in an interview with Telegraph.
For the first time this year, a course will guide students about how proper sleep habits support academic and athletic performances and improve overall well-being.
Professor of Harvard University Medical Faculty and Deputy Director of University Health Services Paul Barreira says that the university ended the course after hearing how students suffered serious sleep deprivations during the study week.
An hour-long course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented a picture of the dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, and thus get information on the effects of caffeine and light and the effect of sleep deprivation on sports performances and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know that this has no immediate effect on students' behavior.
However, we believe that they have the right to know these things in exactly the same way as they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking," Professor Czeisler adds.
All night long study marathons are, according to Professor Czeisler, still a subject of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures of students made the sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Geting adequate and high quality sleep should be a 'secret weapon' against stress, fatigue, and anxiety among students, and even against weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a space similar to starvation in the brain, which makes man constantly hungry," the professor notes.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical psychology, helped Professor Czeisler to plan the course after he had attended one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He reports that the course opened his eyes and gave the impetus to organize a course covering all campus students.
He hopes that all graduate students could complete a similar study package before entering a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends setting an alarm clock for students to also remind them of bedtime in addition to waking up in the morning and urges them to bear in mind the effects of electronic display devices and LED lighting on the "blue light" cycle, which may make it difficult to fall asleep.
