A New German Warship Delays Again
The latest frigate in the German fleet should have been introduced in 2014. The purpose of the ship is to replace obsolete Cold War equipment, but it will be introduced at the earliest next year due to faulty systems and explosively increasing costs, according to local media.
According to a military spokesperson for Die Zeit, the introduction of the ‘Rheinland-Pfalzin', the new first ship of the Baden-Württemberg frigate class, has been postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship was to join the fleet in 2014, but worrying post-delivery problems have haunted an ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg class ships commissioned by the Navy in 2007 are scheduled to replace the aging Bremen class frigates.
According to the information available, they are equipped with an effective cannon, missile systems to control aircraft and surface vessels, and stealth technology such as radar reflectivity, infrared and acoustic signal detection.
The important features of the ship also include its longer service interval – new frigates should be able to operate at sea for up to two years without visiting the home port.
However, constant delays mean that technology-driven warships – the purpose of which is said to be to improve German influence in the overseas territories – are already obsolete at the time of their entry into service, Die Zeit notes.
The unfortunate F125 frigate ended up in headlines last year when the German Navy formally refused to introduce the ship and returned it to Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet will return the ship after it has been delivered.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but there has been talk in German media of essential "software and hardware failures" that make a warship unfit for combat duties.
The software deficiencies are particularly central to the fact that the crew of Baden-Württemberg-class ships is about 120, which is only half of the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
It also emerged that the ship is significantly overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the fleet's chances of subsequent updates.
It is believed that Rheinland-Pfalz, of its capacity of 7,000 tonnes, is twice as heavy as the equivalent class of ships used by Germany in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the whole price tag of the project is also becoming a problem.
The price is reported to have risen to a stunning sum of EUR 3.1 billion, compared with EUR 2.2 billion in the original price.
The problems of introducing new frigates have been raised as the German maritime power has recently been warned of shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, director of the German Parliament's Defence Committee, pointed out earlier this year that the fleet's usable ships "are running low".
According to the Authority, the problem has grown over time due to the decommissioning of old vessels, but no new ones have been submitted.
He lamented that no Baden-Württemberg-class frigate could have been introduced by the Navy.
The environmental organization is listening to the hidden lives of bats
A new study in the Highlands of Scotland aims to find out how bats use the terrain to hunt for food.
New research is hoped to shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and to guide future conservation measures.
Research carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland is being monitored for bats of pests and dwarfs, as well as ear bugs and water wings in the area of Inverewe Garden, a botanical garden in Wester Ross.
In the study, special storage devices are placed in important areas of the area to monitor the operation of bats during the period.
Workers and volunteers of the organisation also carry out mobile measurements using portable observation equipment.
The frequency of the votes, as well as the species concerned, shall be ensured by the analysis of the experts.
Based on the results, a habitat map and report will be created in which bat behaviour can be presented in a scale image of the area.
Rob Dewar, the organization's nature conservation advisor hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are the most important for bats, and how different species exploit them.
This information helps in the planning of habitat areas, such as the creation of meadows and the management of forest areas, taking bats and related species into account.
The bat populations in Scotland and the whole of Great Britain have decreased considerably over the last 100 years.
Construction and civil engineering are threatening bats' resting places and habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as flypapers and certain chemicals used in construction materials, as well as attacks on pet cats.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, because of night hunting practices, their ears are more beneficial in catching catch than in the eyes.
Bats use advanced echo tracking techniques to detect insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
National Trust for Scotland is an organization focused on protecting the rural environment that maintains over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens, and 76,000 hectares of areas across the country – and they take bats seriously.
It employs ten experts who regularly conduct surveys, ramp inspections and, in some cases, animal rescue activities.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only reserve for the protection of bats on the lands of the Threave Manor in the Dumfries and Galloway area. Eight of the ten bat species in Scotland are found in the area.
According to farm manager David Thompson, the area is ideal for bats.
"Threave suits bats very well," he says.
"We have old buildings and trees and a good living environment overall.
The bats are not yet known everything, so our work here and in other areas of the organization will help us to understand better what bats need to succeed."
He emphasizes the importance of checking the buildings for bats before embarking on refurbishment, as the destruction of one of the bats' resting places may inadvertently cause the death of up to 400 female bats and chicks and destroy an entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and killing, disturbing or destroying their resting places is forbidden.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official of the Bat Protection Organization, encourages the public to participate in the conservation work.
He says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we still don't know how their populations are doing."
