According to the FWC, more fragmented algal areas are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, indicating a possible decrease in concentrations.
Red Tide algae bloom extends off the coast for about 130 miles from Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
Ferries can be detected ten miles from the Hillsborough County coast, but there are fewer than last week.
Red Tide algae bloom has also been observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations were reported from the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, concentrations ranged from low to high levels on the coasts of Hillsborough County, from background concentrations to high concentrations in Manate and Sarasota counties, from background concentration to moderate concentrations in Charlotte County and from background concentration to high concentrations on the coasts of Lee District Court and Collier County with low lengths.
Respiratory symptoms are further reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the last week, no signs of respiratory symptoms occurred in the northwest of Florida.
